articles.author: Howard Schneider, Lindsay Dunsmuir
articles.description: Third-quarter U.S. economic growth, at an annualized 4.9% rate, was a "blowout" performance that warrants watching as the Federal Reserve considers its next policy moves, Fed Governor Christopher Waller said on Tuesday.
articles.title: Fed's Waller calls Q3 US GDP growth a 'blowout' number that warrants watching

articles.author: Katie Paul
articles.description: A former Meta (META.O) employee is testifying before a U.S. Senate subcommittee on Tuesday, alleging that the Facebook and Instagram parent company was aware of harassment and other harms facing teens on its platforms but failed to address them.
articles.title: Former Meta employee tells Senate company failed to protect teens' safety

articles.author: Douglas Gillison, Hannah Lang
articles.description: The top U.S. consumer financial watchdog on Tuesday proposed to regulate tech giants' digital payments and smartphone wallet services, saying they rival traditional payment methods in scale and scope but lack consumer safeguards.
articles.title: US consumer watchdog proposes rules for Big Tech payments, digital wallets

articles.author: Jeffrey Goldfarb
articles.description: There’s a spanner in the freshly restarted U.S. manufacturing machine. A factory construction boom sparked by President Joe Biden’s industrial policies has led to unbridled optimism about the sector for the first time in decades. The hardest part of the process hangs in the balance, however: filling all the anticipated job openings.
articles.title: Workers are missing cog in US manufacturing gears

articles.author: Blake Brittain
articles.description: Footwear giant Nike (NKE.N) filed federal lawsuits on Monday against rivals New Balance and Skechers (SKX.N), accusing them of infringing patents related to Nike's technology for making upper portions of sneakers.
articles.title: Nike sues New Balance, Skechers for patent infringement over sneaker technology

articles.author: David Shepardson
articles.description: Four large pickup trucks fared poorly in protecting back seat passengers in tests measuring how those passengers fare in some crashes, the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety said on Tuesday.
articles.title: Large pickup trucks fare poorly in protecting back seat passengers -study

articles.author: Joice Alves, Danilo Masoni
articles.description: Italian stocks are trading at their deepest discount in 35 years compared to world shares as investors fret over the fiscal outlook in one of Europe's most indebted economies, although some reckon the shares are too cheap to ignore.
articles.title: Growing Italy risk puts equities at deepest discount in 35 years

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Emily Rose
articles.description: Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Israel would consider "tactical little pauses" in Gaza fighting to facilitate the entry of aid or the exit of hostages, but again rejected calls for a general ceasefire despite growing international pressure.
articles.title: Israel says it is open to Gaza fighting pauses for aid, hostages

articles.author: Jarrett Renshaw
articles.description: Andrea Singmaster is thankful for President Joe Biden. He helped secure funding to clean up a contaminated site in her Philadelphia suburb and his efforts to crack down on Medicare drug prices will help family members financially manage arthritis and Crohn's disease.
articles.title: Democrats' dilemma: Biden's agenda is popular, but he is not

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Flexible workspace provider WeWork (WE.N) sought U.S. bankruptcy protection on Monday, crippled by a large debt pile and soaring losses due to lower demand for office space from cost-conscious customers.
articles.title: Explainer: Why WeWork failed, and what is next
